 igh\nSource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nSource: AU ABS\nImpact: high\nOfficia
 l ABS series page release date. Time zone shown by ABS: AEST.\n\nExplain
 er:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Change in the
  prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and services.\n\n• Usu
 al market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is usually bullish for 
 the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because markets may price in 
 higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one of the most w
 atched inflation indicators because it can quickly shift central-bank ra
 te expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Australian CPI has
  both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI releases.\n\n• Note
 s: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and energy to give a cle
 aner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms: CPI = Consu
 mer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au/statistics/e
 conomy/price-indexes-and-inflation/consumer-price-index-australia\n\nExp
 lainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Change in
  the prices paid by consumers for a basket of goods and services.\n\n•
  Usual market effect: Higher-than-forecast inflation is usually bullish 
 for the local currency and bearish for bonds\, because markets may price
  in higher interest rates.\n\n• Why traders care: CPI is one of the mo
 st watched inflation indicators because it can quickly shift central-ban
 k rate expectations.\n\n• Frequency: US CPI is monthly. Australian CPI
  has both monthly indicator releases and quarterly CPI releases.\n\n• 
 Notes: Core CPI removes volatile items such as food and energy to give a
  cleaner read on underlying inflation pressure.\n\n• Acronyms: CPI = C
 onsumer Price Index.\n\nOfficial source: https://www.abs.gov.au/statisti
 cs/economy/price-indexes-and-inflation/consumer-price-index-australia\n\
 nExplainer:\n• What it is: Consumer Price Index\n\n• Measures: Chang
